Run a quick profile about containsAll() of Set.
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    Set<String> set;
    List<String> input = new ArrayList<>();
    Random ran = new Random();
    for (int i = 0; i < 10000000; i++)  {
      input.add("test" + ran.nextInt() + i);
    }
    long start = System.currentTimeMillis();
    set = new HashSet<>(input);
    long mid = System.currentTimeMillis();
    set.containsAll(input);
    long end = System.currentTimeMillis();
    System.out.println("Phase I: " + (mid - start) + " Phase II: " + (end - mid));
  }

The result is Phase I: 5560 Phase II: 1242
So containsAll is not a major concern here. I think.
Actually, I also compared with List.containsAll(), that one is for sure O(N^2). It took forever to run in my laptop.

